i>, <i>hūs</i>).","variant of   Woodiwiss  , from Middle English <i>wodewose</i>, which by the 16th century was sometimes written as <i>wodowes</i>, <i>woodose</i>, and <i>wodehouse</i>. The confusion with <i>woodhouse</i> probably arose because both words (and both names) were pronounced /wudus/ or /wudǝs/ in local dialect.","English:"],"variants":[{"name":"Woodis","meanings":["English:","perhaps a nickname from Old English <i>wuduwāsa</i>‘faun, satyr’.","alternatively, a shortened form of   Woodhouse  ."]},{"name":"Woodiwiss","meanings":["English (mainly Derbyshire and Yorkshire): nickname from Middle English <i>wodewose</i>, <i>wodewese</i> (Old English <i>wudewāse</i>) ‘wild man of the woods’. This word was also used to denote a person dressed to represent such a being in a play or pageant. Wodewoses (male and female) were mythical creatures of English and ancient Germanic folklore, akin to the fauns and satyrs of Classical mythology. The surname may also have been acquired by someone who lived and worked in the woods or perhaps by an unusually hairy man."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705192,"age":8,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":17,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705195,"age":62,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Thomas Woodhouse I was born in 1320, in Kimberley, Norfolk, England, his father, Richard Woodhouse I, was 26 and his mother, Alice Northwood, was 21. He married Alice Gilmond about 1340, in Kimberley, Norfolk, England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons."},"et":{"1320–":"1320–Surnud","1320–Male":"1320–Surnud","1322–Female":"1322–Surnud","1300–Female":"1300–Surnud","1340–1378":"1340–1378","1350–1430":"1350–1430","1295–Male":"1295–Surnud","1340":"1340","1350":"1350","1295":"1295","1382":"1382","1337":"1337","about 1319":"umbes 1319","1378":"1378","1300":"1300","1322":"1322","1453":"1453","1320":"1320","1430":"1430","about 1340":"umbes 1340","1328":"1328","Kimberley, Norfolkshire, England":"Kimberley, Norfolk, England","Kimberley, Norfolk, England":"Kimberley, Norfolk, England","Kimberley, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom":"Kimberley, Norfolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1320–":"1320–Kuollut","1320–Male":"1320–Kuollut","1322–Female":"1322–Kuollut","1300–Female":"1300–Kuollut","1340–1378":"1340–1378","1350–1430":"1350–1430","1295–Male":"1295–Kuollut","1340":"1340","1350":"1350","1295":"1295","1382":"1382","1337":"1337","about 1319":"noin 1319","1378":"1378","1300":"1300","1322":"1322","1453":"1453","1320":"1320","1430":"1430","about 1340":"no